## Installation
While in a production environment, the Process Engine is typically hosted on a server or integrated with another server application, for designing processes a local installation can be useful. This section gives a quick overview of how to install a basic Process Engine instance for running processes locally. We expect that Java has been installed and configured on your system (for detailed system requirements, please see the Administration Reference).

Process Engine is provided as a set of directories containing the necessary binaries, this documentation and some example and reference files. This directory structure is called the Process Engine distribution. The distribution also contains the bundler tool which can be used to create a Process Engine installation.

For the remainder of the quick start documentation, we assume that the Process Engine will be installed on a Windows system in the folder `C:\doxee\process-engine\`. To create a basic installation of the Process Engine, open a command prompt, navigate to the distribution’s `bundler` directory, and execute the following command:

`java -jar bundler.jar -t C:/doxee/process-engine/ -b cmd core base fop`This will copy all the necessary files to the target directory, in this case a command line version of the Process Engine (`cmd`) with the modules `core`, `base `and `fop`. The `core` and base modules provide common activities and XPath functions and should always be installed, while the `fop` module contains the Apache FOP renderer commonly used to render Doxee templates. The target directory will also contain a default version of the configuraton file `process_engine.xml`, which can be modified to change the Process Engine’s settings.

To verify that the Process Engine installation was successful, the command line client can be started with the `-version` option, which should display the version of the Process Engine installation:

`C:
cd \doxee\process-engine
java -jar infinica-process-engine.jar -version`## Integrating With Process Designer
The newly installed command line version of the Process Engine can be called from the system’s command line or integrated with Process Designer. This allows you to design processes visually and simply start them by clicking a button.

For detailed information please refer to the Process Designer documentation.

## A Simple Process
Now that the Process Engine installation is ready, we can start with a simple process:

![](data:image/png;base64,)*Figure 1. simple.ipd*

You can find this process in the file `examples/simple.ipd.`

To run it from Process Designer, simply open the file in the designer, click the arrow next to the Execute button in the toolbar and select `Launch Configurations`. A matching launch configuration will be prepared automatically and can be executed using the `Launch` button.

Note that the only thing our process actually does is write to stdout, which is not visible when running the process from Process Designer. However, you can also run the process from the command line. For this, first copy the file `simple.ipd` to `C:\doxee\processengine\`. Then, in a console, run the following command in the Process Engine directory:

`java -jar infinica-process-engine.jar simple.ipd`Let’s have a closer look at the process to see how it does what it does.

A process primarily consists of elements and connections, which are collectively called process components. These components form a graph, with the elements as the nodes and the connections as the edges of the graph, as displayed above. Each element represents specific functionality performed when process execution reaches the element, while connections define how process execution should continue after each element has been executed.

Process execution always begins at the *start element*, which is a necessary part of every process. In this simple example, marking the beginning of the process is the start element’s only function.

Each process element has at least two properties: An ID and a name. The ID is mandatory Process Designer always assigns a new ID when creating an element, but even if it is not specified in the process definition, an ID will automatically be generated by the Process Engine when reading the process definition. Each element’s ID must be unique and can be used to reference its specific element in the process.

By contrast, a component’s name is optional and does not have any specific restrictions. It is simply used as a label in process diagrams. Multiple components may share the same name. If an element does not have a name, diagrams will display the ID instead.

Elements are connected by connections. A connection always points from one element (the source element) to another element (the target element). To the source element, the connection is known as its outgoing connection. To the target element, is is known as the incoming connection. Most elements can have any number of incoming connections and exactly one outgoing connection. Two exceptions are the start element, which never has an incoming connection, and the end element, which never has an outgoing connection. Connections, like elements, have IDs and names with exactly the same properties as described above.

In the above example, the start element’s outgoing connection leads to the element *Print Hello*, which is therefore executed as soon as the start element has been processed.

*Print Hello* is an activity element, which is the type of element you will most frequently find in process definitions. It executes a specific activity, which is implemented independently from the process definition and usually defined in a generic fashion allowing it to be reused by different processes. The Process Engine provides a range of activities out of the box, including activities for reading resources from a URL, writing them to a URL, performing an XSL translation, etc. Further activities can be installed on demand to provides ways for sending emails, modifying PDF documents or performing whatever other functionality is required by a process - if necessary, a developer can create a new activity from scratch and deploy it to an existing Process Engine installation.

An activity element specifies which activity to use through its descriptor attribute, which has to match the ID of an activity available in the Process Engine. In this case, we use the `printActivity` activity, which simply writes some text to `stdout `(i.e. the console, if the process is started from the command line).

Our only activity’s outgoing connection leads to the process’s *end element*, which finishes the process execution and ends the process in a successful state. A process can have multiple end elements, but since our demo process only has one branch of execution, only one end element is required.

## The Pipeline
Most activities are defined to provide very specific functionality, usually carrying out one single task like reading a resource, writing a file, sending an email or transforming an XML structure. On their own, these activities are not of much use - they develop their full potential by working together with other activities in a process. Activities interact by exchanging data through variables.

The storage where variables are held at runtime is called the pipeline. The pipeline is usually accessed through mappings defined on process elements, e.g. on mapping or activity elements. For activities, this is the only way to exchange data between the process pipeline and the activity, since the activity itself does not have access to the process pipeline. Instead, they define input and output parameters, which can be access by an activity element’s input and output mappings. The input mappings read from the process pipeline and write to the activity’s elements before the activity is executed, while the output mappings are called after execution to map the activity’s output parameters back to the process pipeline.

To allow a process to exchange data with its caller, start and end elements also support mappings. A start element’s mappings define the process’s input parameters by mapping values provided by the caller into the process pipeline, while the end element’s mappings map variables from the process pipeline back to the caller when the process ends, thus providing its output parameters.

A process may have more than one pipeline during its lifecycle. For example, sub structures like groups and loops have their own pipelines.

Our first process already used a primitive mapping that passes the text *Hello World!* to the print activity:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 2. "Hello World!" mapping*

In this case, the mapping’s source is a simple string literal, i.e. a text string that does not depend on the current variables in the pipeline. The mapping’s target is the variable input, which for the print activity is the parameter which defines what the activity should output.

Let’s take things one step further and upgrade the process to support an input parameter which determines the process’s output text. The new process can be found in the file `examples/simple_with_params.ipd:`

![](data:image/png;base64,)*Figure 3. simple_with_params.ipd*

The process diagram itself doesn’t look different than before. But the start element now has a mapping:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 4. Start element mapping*

The process parameter in this example is called text. As in most cases, this is also the name of the process variable we want to store the parameter’s value in.

To use the new variable in our print activity, we also have to change the activity element’s mapping from the previous literal source to a variable source:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 5. Activity mapping*

Now, the variable text from the process pipeline is mapped to the activity’s input parameter.

Running the process from the command line, we now must specify the process’s mandatory text parameter. If we don’t, the Process Engine will report an error message:

`java -jar infinica-process-engine.jar simple_with_params.ipd`If we call the process with the required parameter, our custom greeting text will be shown as the process’s output:

`java -jar infinica-process-engine.jar simple_with_params.ipd "text=Hello User!"`> Note

Since our custom text includes a space character, we have to quote it to make sure the console uses it as a single parameter. Parameters are always passed to the Process Engine as single command line parameter in the format `parameter=value`. Therefore, our quotes must include the parameter name and equals sign (=).

## XPath Queries
Variable sources let you to transfer values from one variable to another, but they don’t allow you to change the values. To perform calculations and other operations on a mapping’s source values, you have to use XPath sources.

An XPath source queries the source pipeline with an XPath expression. The expression can access any variable in the source pipeline as an XPath variable (using the `$variable` syntax).

Let’s take a look at the following process, which you can find in the file `examples/calc.ipd:`

![](data:image/png;base64,)*Figure 6. calc.ipd*

The start element has two mappings for the parameters a and b.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 7. Start element mapping*

These parameters are assigned the type `x-xsd/integer` to make sure that:

- only integer values can be specified by the caller (and non-integer parameter values will raise an exception), and

- the variables are internally known to be numbers, so that calculations (see below) are carried out correctly.

This process uses a mapping element. Mapping elements simply execute a list of mappings, with both the source and target variables located in the process pipeline. They are therefore ideal for calculations and data preparation steps.

The mapping element in our demo process is called *Calculate Sum* and has the following mapping:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 8. Calculate Sum mapping*

This assigns an XPath source to the target variable c. The XPath expression is `$a + $b`, reading the variables a and b from the pipeline and calculating their sum. The addition operator (+) works correctly because the pipeline variables have already been defined as integer values by the start element.

The process also has a print activity like our earlier example process. This time, however, its mapping uses a parameterised literal source:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 9. Print mapping*

A parameterised literal is a string literal that can have dynamic parts. The dynamic parts are represented by XPath expressions wrapped in curly braces (`{}`). Each of these expressions will be evaluated and its result converted to a string to form the final value of the literal.

In this example, the literal is `{$a} + {$b} = {$c}`, which inserts the pipeline variables a, b and c into the literal to produce output of the following sort:

`13 + 29 = 42`Of course, the same result could be achived with a plain XPath source, but the corresponding XPath expression would be a little more complicated:

`concat($a, ' + ', $b, ' = ', $c)`Parameterised literals are a simple and readable way to combine XPath queries with static text.

Finally, the end element also has a mapping, which returns the result of our calculation to the caller:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 10. End mapping*

Calling the process from the command line shows the following output:

`java -jar infinica-process-engine.jar calc_params.ipd a=13 b=29`However, the command line does not provide access to the process’s return value. We can see that by running the process from Process Designer.

> Note

Every variable source referring to a variable `name` can also be written as an XPath source using the expression `$name`.

Every XPath source executing the expression `expr` and using it as a string can also be written as a parameterised literal source using the literal `{expr}.`

XPath expressions within curly braces can also be used in variable sources. In this case, the *name* of the variable to be read is determined by the result of the XPath query.

## Logging
When creating a new process, it is often useful to peek into variables and verify their values while the process is running. If an error occurs, this can help determine its cause. During the testing phase, it can be even more helpful , as developers will often find a dump of variables more helpful than the descriptions of testing personnel. Even at the production stage, certain values and runtime states of process executions can be useful to gather usage statistics.

The Process Engine’s logging framework facilitates all these use cases. Instead of tediously writing values to stdout using print activities, log elements in the process definition can use the diagnostic log to write logging information to a dedicated stream, file or database. Additionally, the Process Engine can log trace information via the trace log, showing which components of a process have been called in which order and at what time. Finally, the data log can be used to write typed values from a process which can later be used for queries and metrics, e.g. to calculate the average number of PDF pages rendered per process.

Of the log types just described, the diagnostic and data logs support log levels, assigning to each log message a level ranging from `debug` to `fatal`. The logging configuration defines a minimum log level, which allows only message of a log level equal or higher than the specified level to be written. This way, when deploying a process from a test to a production system, the log statements used for testing do not have to be removed from the process definition. Instead, the production system will simply use a different logging configuration, filtering all log levels below e.g. the `warn` level.

In a process definition, diagnostic and data log directives can be used at various locations, including:

- At the beginning and end of the process

- At the beginning and/or end of most process element

- On connections

- On conditions

A log message will be written whenever a log directive is passed during process execution,

e.g. when an activity is about to be executed (for a log directive specified at the beginning of the activity element), when an activity has been executed (for a log directive specified at the end of the activity element) or when a connection is taken. The message associated with a diagnostic log directive follows the same rules as a parameterised literal source and may therefore use XPath expressions to include the values of pipeline variables.

The example process `examples/logging.ipd` uses several diagnostic logging directives:

![](data:image/png;base64,)*Figure 11. logging.ipd*

Diagnostic logging directives, not visible in the process diagram, are placed on the following components:

- At the beginning of the process.

- On the start element.

- At the beginning of the `Print` activity element.

- At the end of the `Print` activity element.

- On the end element.

- At the end of the process.

Running the process from Process Designer will show the process’s log output.

For development and test environments, stdout or a text file can be a useful target for log output. On a production system, logging to a database is usually a better solution, as the database can be automatically purged and efficiently queried. This is especially useful for data log output, which can be used to calculate metrics using database queries. A logging database has a fixed structure; database creation scripts for the most common database systems are provided in the installation package.
